check for admin interfaces\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Findings\n\n### Module 2 \u2014 MQTT Attack Suite\n**Target:** localhost:1883\n\n#### CRITICAL \u2014 Connection Test\n\n**Finding:** BROKER ACCEPTS ANONYMOUS CONNECTIONS \u2014 No authentication required\n\n**Recommendation:** Configure MQTT broker authentication. Enable username/password authentication in mosquitto.conf: `allow_anonymous false`. Generate strong unique credentials for each client.\n\n#### CRITICAL \u2014 Authentication Bypass\n\n**Finding:** Authentication bypass successful \u2014 17 valid credential set(s) found\n\n**Valid Credentials Found:** 17\n\n**Recommendation:** Change all default MQTT credentials immediately. Implement per-device unique credentials. Consider certificate-based authentication for production deployments.\n\n#### \ud83d\udccb INFO \u2014 Topic Enumeration\n\n**Finding:** No messages captured in window\n\n#### HIGH \u2014 Message Injection\n\n**Finding:** Message injection successful \u2014 4 message(s) injected without authorisation\n\n#### CRITICAL \u2014 Sensitive Data Harvest\n\n**Finding:** 4 sensitive data pattern(s) found in MQTT traffic\n\n**Recommendation:** Review all MQTT topic payloads for sensitive data. Implement payload encryption using TLS (port 8883). Apply topic-level access control lists (ACLs).\n\n#### \ud83d\udccb INFO \u2014 Retained Message Scanner\n\n**Finding:** No retained messages found\n\n---\n\n### Module 4 \u2014 HTTP/Web IoT Suite\n**Target:** http://localhost:8080\n\n#### CRITICAL \u2014 Default Credential Testing\n\n**Finding:** Default credentials valid \u2014 24 credential set(s) found\n\n**Recommendation:** Change all default credentials immediately. Implement account lockout after failed attempts. Use strong unique passwords for each device. Consider disabling the web interface if not needed.\n\n#### CRITICAL \u2014 Admin Interface Discovery\n\n**Finding:** 8 interface(s) found \u2014 8 exposing sensitive data\n\n**Recommendation:** Restrict admin interface access by IP whitelist. Implement strong authentication on all admin pages. Consider moving admin interface to non-standard port. Disable admin interface if not required remotely.\n\n#### CRITICAL \u2014 API Security Testing\n\n**Finding:** 2 API(s) found \u2014 2 exposing sensitive data without authentication\n\n**Recommendation:** Remove all sensitive data from HTTP responses. Implement proper access control on all API endpoints. Audit all endpoints for unintended data exposure. Implement API authentication tokens.\n\n#### LOW \u2014 Common Vulnerability Scan\n\n**Finding:** 2 vulnerability/vulnerabilities found\n\n---\n\n## AI-Powered Risk Analysis\n\nThe following analysis was generated by AIPET's Explainable AI engine using a Random Forest classifier trained on IoT CVE data and SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) values to justify each prediction.\n\n### \u2139\ufe0f  LOW \u2014 Device: 127.0.0.1\n\n**Device Type:** embedded_linux_device\n**AI Predicted Severity:** Low (73.8% confidence)\n\n**Severity Probability Breakdown:**\n\n| Severity | Probability |\n|----------|-------------|\n| Low | 73.8% \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588 |\n| Medium | 22.7% \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588 |\n| High | 3.0%  |\n| Critical | 0.5%  |\n\n**Key Factors (SHAP Feature Contributions):**\n\n| Feature | Impact | Direction |\n|---------|--------|-----------|\n| Firmware Vulnerable Component | 12.0% | \u2b06\ufe0f Increases severity |\n| Device Type | 10.2% | \u2b06\ufe0f Increases severity |\n| Firmware Hardcoded Creds | 7.4% | \u2b06\ufe0f Increases severity |\n| Open Port Count | 4.2% | \u2b06\ufe0f Increases severity |\n| Http Default Creds | 3.2% | \u2b06\ufe0f Increases severity |\n| Mqtt Anonymous | 2.6% | \u2b06\ufe0f Increases severity |\n| Http Admin Exposed | 2.3% | \u2b06\ufe0f Increases severity |\n| Port 22 | 1.8% | \u2b07\ufe0f Reduces severity |\n\n**Plain-English Explanation:**\n\n```\nPredicted Severity: Low (confidence: 73.8%)\n\nKey factors driving this prediction:\n\n  Increasing severity:\n  + Device type classification (impact: 10.2%)\n  + Total number of open ports (impact: 4.2%)\n\n  Reducing severity:\n  - SSH service (port 22) (impact: 1.8%)\n  - Alternative HTTP interface (port 8080) (impact: 1.2%)\n\nSeverity probability breakdown:\n  Low         73.8%  \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\n  Medium      22.7%  \u2588\u2588\u2588\u2588\n  High         3.0%  \n  Critical     0.5%  \n```\n\n---\n\n## Recommendations\n\nThe following recommendations are prioritised by severity. Address Critical items immediately before moving to High severity items.\n\n### \ud83d\udea8 Critical Priority\n\n1. **Disable anonymous MQTT access** \u2014 Enforce authentication on all MQTT brokers. No device should connect without credentials.\n\n2. **Remove hardcoded credentials from firmware** \u2014 Issue firmware update. All devices running affected firmware are vulnerable.\n\n3. **Revoke and replace shared private keys** \u2014 Every device sharing the same key is vulnerable to traffic decryption and impersonation.\n\n4. **Disable Telnet** \u2014 Replace with SSH on all devices. Telnet exposes credentials on the network.\n\n### \ud83d\udd34 High Priority\n\n5. **Change all default web interface credentials** \u2014 Each device must have unique, strong credentials.\n\n6. **Restrict admin interface access** \u2014 Admin panels should not be accessible without authentication. Apply IP whitelisting where possible.\n\n7. **Update vulnerable firmware components** \u2014 OpenSSL 1.0.x and OpenSSH < 7.4 have known critical vulnerabilities. Update immediately.\n\n### \u26a0\ufe0f Medium Priority\n\n8. **Implement CoAP authentication** \u2014 Use DTLS for CoAP communication. Restrict resource access to authorised clients.\n\n9. **Implement replay protection** \u2014 Add nonce or timestamp validation to CoAP and MQTT message processing.\n\n10. **Add HTTP security headers** \u2014 Implement X-Frame-Options, Content-Security-Policy, and X-Content-Type-Options on all web interfaces.\n\n### \u2139\ufe0f General Best Practices\n\n- Implement network segmentation \u2014 IoT devices should be on isolated VLANs\n- Enable firmware automatic updates where possible\n- Monitor all IoT device communications for anomalous behaviour\n- Conduct regular penetration testing as devices and firmware are updated\n- Subscribe to CVE notifications for all IoT device models and firmware versions\n\n---\n\n*Report generated by AIPET \u2014 AI-Powered Penetration Testing Framework for IoT*\n*Coventry University \u2014 MSc Cyber Security (Ethical Hacking) \u2014 2025*\n*This report is confidential and intended solely for the authorised recipient.*"
